{"title_page": "Under the Yoke", "text_new": "{{about||the 1918 film starring Theda Bara|Under the Yoke (film)|the novel by S. M. Stirling|Under the Yoke (Stirling novel)}}\n{{italic title}}\n[[Image:IvanVazov.jpeg|frame|Ivan Vazov]]\n\n'''''Under the Yoke''''' [Bulgarian: ''''\u041f\u043e\u0434 \u0438\u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e''''- ''Pod Igoto''] is a novel by [[Ivan Vazov]] written in 1888.<ref>See {{cite book |last=Vazoff |first=Ivan |title=Under the Yoke: A Romance of Bulgarian Liberty with An Introduction by Edmund Gosse |publisher= William Heinemann |place=London |year= 1912 |page= viii|url=https://archive.org/stream/underyokeromance00vazorich#page/n13/mode/2up|accessdate= 17 June 2018 |via= Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Keller |first= Helen Rex|chapter=Under the Yoke (\"Pod Igoto) |title=The Reader's Digest of Books |publisher= The Macmillan Company|place=New York |year=1923 |pages=868-869 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pst.000065653180;view=1up;seq=880 |accessdate= June 17, 2018|via= HathiTrust Digital Collection}}</ref> It is set in a small town in Central Bulgaria during the months leading up to the April Uprising in 1876 and is the most famous piece of classic [[Bulgarian literature]]. ''Under the Yoke'' has been translated into more than 30 languages and it is the first ever Bulgarian novel to be written.\n\n==Plot==\nThe tranquility in a Bulgarian village under [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule is only superficial: the people are quietly preparing for an uprising. The plot follows the story of Boycho Ognyanov, who, having escaped from a prison in [[Diyarbakir|Diarbekir]], returns to the Bulgarian town of Byala Cherkva (White Church, fictional representation of [[Sopot, Plovdiv Province|Sopot]]) to take part in the rebellion. There he meets old friends, enemies, and the love of his life. The plot portrays the personal drama of the characters, their emotions, motives for taking part in or standing against the rebellion, betrayal and conflict.\n\nHistorically, the April Uprising of 1876 failed due to bad organization, limited resources, and betrayal. The brutal way in which the Ottomans broke down the uprising became the pretext for the [[Russo-Turkish War (1877\u20131878)|Russian-Turkish war]],<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/warineastillustr00scheiala/warineastillustr00scheiala_djvu.txt] Illustrated history of the Russo-Turkish war in 1877-1878 </ref> that brought about Bulgarian independence.\n\nThe book has many autobiographical elements: Sopot is the writer's hometown, and he did take a personal part in the uprising described.\n\n==Reactions==\nMary C. Neuburger has described the novel's coffeehouse scenes as a \"social panorama\" of Ganko's ''kafene'' (small Bulgarian coffeehouse) featuring a \"parade of archetypal characters from a Balkan mountain town in Ottoman Bulgaria who drink bitter coffee, ruminate, and debate, laugh and observe, within a 'dense fog of tobacco smoke'\". She writes that Vazov \"skillfully paints a late Ottoman landscape\" leading to the April Uprising of 1876.<Ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Cornell University Press| last = Mary C. Neuburger| title = Balkan Smoke: Tobacco and the Making of Modern Bulgaria| chapter = Coffeehouse Babble: Smoking and Sociability in the Long Nineteenth Century| date = 2013| jstor = 10.7591/j.cttq43m0.5}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptation into films==\n''Under the Yoke'' has been twice adapted into films :\n* 1952 : ''Under the Yoke'' (\u041f\u043e\u0434 \u0438\u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e) by Dako Dakovski <ref> See : [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0197521/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm Dako Dakovski's biography] on IMDb </ref> . [[Sylvie Vartan]], then a seven year little girl, plays the role of a schoolgirl under tensely ''patriotic'' end-of-year examination. The movie is available in its original version, in Bulgarian : [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xYIhuH061RA \u041f\u043e\u0434 \u0438\u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e / Under the yoke (1952)]\n* 1990 :''Under the Yoke'' (\u041f\u043e\u0434 \u0438\u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e) by Yanko Yankov <ref> See : [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0946146/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm Yanko Yankov's biography] on IMDb </ref>. A production in nine parts for Bulgarian television.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*Text of ''[https://archive.org/details/underyokeromance00vazorich Under the Yoke]'' at the Internet Archive\n\n[[Category:1894 novels]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian novels]]\n[[Category:Ottoman period in the history of Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Books about Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Novels about revolutionaries]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian books]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the Ottoman Empire]]\n\n{{Bulgaria-stub}}\n{{1890s-novel-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about||the 1918 film starring Theda Bara|Under the Yoke (film)|the novel by S. M. Stirling|Under the Yoke (Stirling novel)}}\n{{italic title}}\n[[Image:IvanVazov.jpeg|frame|Ivan Vazov]]\n\n'''''Under the Yoke''''' [Bulgarian: ''''\u041f\u043e\u0434 \u0438\u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e''''- ''Pod Igoto''] is a novel by [[Ivan Vazov]] written in 1888.<ref>See {{cite book |last=Vazoff |first=Ivan |title=Under the Yoke: A Romance of Bulgarian Liberty with An Introduction by Edmund Gosse |publisher= William Heinemann |place=London |year= 1912 |page= viii|url=https://archive.org/stream/underyokeromance00vazorich#page/n13/mode/2up|accessdate= 17 June 2018 |via= Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Keller |first= Helen Rex|chapter=Under the Yoke (\"Pod Igoto) |title=The Reader's Digest of Books |publisher= The Macmillan Company|place=New York |year=1923 |pages=868-869 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pst.000065653180;view=1up;seq=880 |accessdate= June 17, 2018|via= HathiTrust Digital Collection}}</ref> It is set in a small town in Central Bulgaria during the months leading up to the April Uprising in 1876 and is the most famous piece of classic [[Bulgarian literature]]. ''Under the Yoke'' has been 